WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish, I'm Phil

4
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Becca

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Have you ever done something physically challenging, Phil?

6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Like running a marathon maybe or climbing a mountain

7
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
I've climbed some mountains but only very little one so it wasn't that challenging

8
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:35.000
If physical challenges are something you enjoy, maybe you should try artistic swimming or synchronize swimming as it used to be called

9
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
A combination of dance and gymnastics with a difference

10
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.000
In artistic swimming athletes dance underwater while holding their breath

11
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Did you say dance underwater?

12
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Yes, swimmer's dance upside down in the water holding their breath

13
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.000
As we'll hear, it's an extremely demanding sport which requires discipline, stamina and years of training

14
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
As usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases

15
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And you can practice these with the quiz and work sheet on our website

16
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
That's BBCLearningEnglish.com

17
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Great

18
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
But first Phil, I have a question for you

19
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Artistics, swimming became an Olympic sport in 1984

20
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.000
But which country has won the most gold medal since then?

21
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Is it A, Russia?

22
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
B, China, or C, the USA?

23
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
I think it's B, China

24
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Well we'll reveal the correct answer later in this episode

25
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Sylvia Solimoshiova from Sevacia is a European championship medalist

26
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:52.000
She's also the first artistic swimmer with over a million social media followers

27
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
After videos of how walking upside down underwater went viral

28
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
Here, she explains the different types of swimming dances

29
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Called routines

30
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
To Dishyane, Navigayam, presenter of BBC World Service Program

31
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.000
The conversation

32
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
If you had to explain statistics swimming to someone who has never seen it

33
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.000
How would you describe it?

34
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
So I would say it depends if you're watching like a solo or a duet or a team routine

35
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Because in solid there's one person in duet there's two people

36
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And in team routines there can be eight people or ten people

37
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And in the team routines there's a lot of lifts

38
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And actually in the routines we are smiling

39
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.000
But we are hiding behind the smile because we are actually maybe dying

40
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
We don't have oxygen so we are smiling and people think that it's easy

41
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.000
When it's actually not

42
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Artistic swimming routines are performed solo

43
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Meaning by just one person or as a duet which means by two people

44
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
There are also team routines where one swimmer is lifted up out of the water

45
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
What all these routines have in common is that physically they are incredibly hard

46
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Yes, artistic routines are done upside down underwater without oxygen

47
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
The swimmer's movements need to be as graceful as a ballet dancer

48
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And above all it has to look effortless because judges award points for artistic expression

49
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Sylvia says she hides behind a smile

50
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
An idea meaning to hide pain by presenting a happy outward appearance

51
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
To succeed at the top level of any sport requires a huge amount of dedication

52
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Sylvia trains eight hours a day six days a week under the guidance of her coach

53
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
He's also her mum and a former artistic swimming champion herself

54
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Here Sylvia discusses the sacrifices she's made to succeed with that she only never knew him

55
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
For BBC World Services the conversation

56
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
How easy was it?

57
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Being trained and coached by your mum

58
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
I think it's good on one side

59
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Because you can practice more at home

60
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:10.000
But on the other hand it's not sometimes good because you're training when you're at home when you're supposed to be like chilling

61
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
There's no respect for me in a way, I guess

62
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Yeah, I didn't have time for anything else

63
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Sylvia thinks they're a good and bad things about being coached by her mum

64
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
It's good because she can practice at home

65
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
But on the other hand it feels like she's training all the time

66
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.000
She uses the phrase on the other hand to show this contrasting opinion

67
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
What Sylvia really looks forward to is chilling

68
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
A slang word meaning relaxing or hanging out

69
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
For young athletes balancing sport with school and friends is difficult

70
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
And it's hard to get a respite from training

71
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
A respite is a temporary break from doing something difficult

72
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Do you know what Becker?

73
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
I think I need a respite from all this talk about training

74
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Now what was the answer to your question?

75
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Ah yes, Phil, I asked you

76
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Which country had won the most gold medals for artistic swimming since the beginning of the Olympic sport?

77
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I said I thought it was China

78
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Well, you're very close to your graphically it is in fact Russia

79
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt

80
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Starts when we've solo, something done alone

81
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And do you add something done by two people?

82
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
The idiom hide behind a smile means to hide painful feelings

83
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
By presenting a happy external appearance

84
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:39.000
The phrase on the other hand is used to introduce a contrasting opinion or statement

85
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
Chilling is slang for relaxing

86
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And finally a respite is a break from doing something difficult

87
